Codebook for U.S. President Returns 1976–2016¶

The data file 1976-2016-president contains constituency (state-level) returns for elections to the U.S. presidency from 1976 to 2016. The data source is the document "Statistics of the Congressional Election," published biennially by the Clerk of the U.S. House of Representatives.

Variables¶

The variables are listed as they appear in the data file.

year¶

  • Description: year in which election was held

office¶

  • Description: U.S. President

state¶

  • Description: state name

state_po¶

  • Description: U.S. postal code state abbreviation

state_fips¶

  • Description: State FIPS code

state_cen¶

  • Description: U.S. Census state code

state_ic¶

  • Description: ICPSR state code

candidate¶

  • Description: name of the candidate
  • Note: The name is as it appears in the House Clerk report.

party¶

  • Description: party of the candidate (always entirely lowercase)
    • Note: Parties are as they appear in the House Clerk report. In states that allow candidates to appear on multiple party lines, separate vote totals are indicated for each party. Therefore, for analysis that involves candidate totals, it will be necessary to aggregate across all party lines within a district. For analysis that focuses on two-party vote totals, it will be necessary to account for major party candidates who receive votes under multiple party labels. Minnesota party labels are given as they appear on the Minnesota ballots. Future versions of this file will include codes for candidates who are endorsed by major parties, regardless of the party label under which they receive votes.

writein¶

  • Description: vote totals associated with write-in candidates
  • Coding:

|:--|:--| | "TRUE" | write-in candidates | | "FALSE" | non-write-in candidates |

candidatevotes¶

  • Description: votes received by this candidate for this particular party
    • Note: Massachusetts and New York returns often contains entries for "blank," "other/blank," "scattering/blank," and the like. For analyses that depend on an accurate count of votes cast for candidates (rather than turnout, including blank ballots), consult state returns. Future versions of this dataset will distinguish blank ballots from votes cast for scattering candidates.

totalvotes¶

  • Description: total number of votes cast for this election

Version¶

  • 20171101

TOP 10 parties' candidate vote counts by year¶

In [312]:
# top 10 parties by total candidate votes in all elections.
parties = (df.groupby('party')
             .agg({'candidatevotes':'sum'})
             .sort_values(by='candidatevotes', ascending=False)
             .head(10).index.values.tolist())
# aggregate candidate votes for each party for each year
data = (df.query(f'party in ({parties})')
          .groupby(['party', 'year'])
          .agg({'candidatevotes':'sum'})
          .reset_index())

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
ax = sns.swarmplot(y="party", x="candidatevotes", hue='year', data=data, size=10)

Total votes growth for all years for top 10 states with most votes¶

In [314]:
def group_apply(grp):
    grp['diff'] = grp.totalvotes.diff()
    grp['pct_change'] = grp.totalvotes.pct_change()
    return grp

states = (data.query('year in (["1976", "2016"])')
              .groupby('state_po')
              .apply(group_apply)
              .sort_values(by='diff', ascending=False)
              .head(10).state_po.values.tolist())

ax = sns.relplot(x='year', y='totalvotes', hue='state_po', kind='line', data=data.query(f'state_po in ({states})'), height=10, aspect=2, color='r')
x = ax.fig.autofmt_xdate()

In the state-wise candidate vote counts for top two parties from 1976-2016, two parties have been the major vote gainers them being Democrat and Republican

In most of the states, both the party candidates have an almost close competition when it comes to vote counts. Ohio, Pennsylvania, Florida, Virgina, West Virginia, Wisconsin, Georgia are some of the states that show this trend through out. Democrat or Republican, either of them occasionally getting upper hand in some years.

Illinois, California and New York are three major states where majorly being republican states before 2000 have turned into democrat strongholds after 2000. Democrat have almost secured doble the votes of Republicans in these states in the latest USA President Election of 2016.

Another major state Texas in the south has been Republican state mostly, especially after 2000.

Fetch top 3 candidates from each year and plot a heatmap of their vote counts¶

In [317]:
## Fetch top 3 candidates from each year and plot a heatmap of their vote counts
def grp_apply(grp):
    grp = grp.reset_index().sort_values(by='candidatevotes', ascending=False).head(3)
    return grp

data = (df.groupby(['year','candidate'])
          .agg({'candidatevotes':'sum'})
          .groupby(['year'])
          .apply(grp_apply)
          .reset_index(drop=True))

pivot = pd.merge(
    data['year'],
    pd.get_dummies(data.candidate),
    on=data.index
).drop('key_0', 1).set_index('year')

pivot = (pivot.stack()
              .reset_index()
              .rename(columns={'level_1':'candidate'})
              .drop(0, 1))

dmerge = pd.merge(
    pivot,
    data[['year', 'candidate', 'candidatevotes']],
    on=['year', 'candidate'],
    how='left'
).fillna(0)

dmerge['candidatevotes'] = dmerge['candidatevotes'].astype(int)

dmerge = (dmerge.reset_index(drop=True)
                .sort_values(by=['year', 'candidate', 'candidatevotes'], ascending=[1, 1, 0])
                .drop_duplicates()
                .pivot('candidate', 'year', 'candidatevotes'))

# plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))
ax = sns.heatmap(dmerge, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap='viridis', cbar=False)
plt.tight_layout()

Vote share percentage for the top candidate in each state categorized by year¶

In [320]:
def gapply(grp):
    grp = grp.sort_values(by='candidatevotes', ascending=False).head(1)
    return grp

data = df.groupby(['year', 'state']).apply(gapply).reset_index(drop=True)
data['vshare_prcnt'] = (data.candidatevotes / data.totalvotes) * 100
filtcols = ['year', 'state_po', 'party', 'vshare_prcnt']
# data[filtcols]

# plot the figure
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
ax = sns.swarmplot(x='state_po', y='vshare_prcnt', hue='year', data=data, size=10)
plt.xlabel('State Postal Code')
plt.ylabel('Vote share percentage')
plt.title('Vote share percentage for the top candidate in each state categorized by year')
plt.show()
